  <article class=3D"col-12 col-sm-10"><router-outlet></router-outlet><app-c=
ronbachs-alpha-desc><h1>Cronbachs Alpha calculator</h1>

<a href=3D"https://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/reliability-analysis/cr=
onbachs-alpha-calculator?example=3DCronbachs_Alpha" role=3D"button" class=
=3D"btn btn-primary mb-3"><i>Load data set</i></a>

<p>
  With numiqo you can calculate Cronbach's alpha online simply select the v=
ariables for
  which you want to calculate the Cronbach's alpha.
</p>
<img alt=3D"calculate Cronbachs Alpha" title=3D"calculate Cronbachs Alpha" =
src=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/calc/calculate_Cronbachs_Alpha.png">
<p>The results of the calculated Cronbach's alpha are then clearly displaye=
d.</p>
<img alt=3D"Cronbachs Alpha calculator" title=3D"Cronbachs Alpha calculator=
" src=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/calc/Cronbachs_Alpha_calculator.png">

<p>
  The following table from George and Mallery (2003) can be used to interpr=
et Cronbach's
  Alpha
</p>

<table class=3D"table result-table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th scope=3D"col">Cronbachs Alpha</th>
      <th scope=3D"col">Interpretation</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <th>&gt; .9</th>
      <th>Excellent</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&gt; .8</th>
      <th>Good</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&gt; .7</th>
      <th>Acceptable</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&gt; .6</th>
      <th>Questionable</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&gt; .5</th>
      <th>Poor</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&lt; .5</th>
      <th>Unacceptable</th>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>
  Values much larger than 0.9 are again considered critical, as this indica=
tes that some
  features are too similar and thus the same thing comes out.
